            . I <rs id="t18310908-253-viclabel1301" type="occupation">keep <placeName id="t18310908-253-crimeloc1302">the Farm and Castle, Little Trinity-lane</placeName>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-crimeloc1302" type="placeName" value="the Farm and Castle, Little Trinity-lane"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-crimeloc1302" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                     <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-253-off1300 t18310908-253-crimeloc1302"></join>
                  </rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310908-253-victim1846 t18310908-253-viclabel1301"></join>. On the 26th of July the prisoner came in, and ordered a pint of beer - he offered my wife a crown-piece, and she called me; she gave me the crown, and I gave it to Oldis.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1847">
                  HARRIET 
                  TYRRELL
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1847" type="surname" value="TYRRELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1847" type="given" value="HARRIET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1847" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the prosecutor's wife. The prisoner gave me the crown-piece; I knew him before, and told him to sit down and wait for his change; I gave it to my husband, suspecting it was not good - there was an officer in the house, to whom we gave it.</p>
               <p>JOHN OLDIS. I am a constable. I was in the house, and saw the prisoner there - I took the prisoner in charge; he was discharged before the Magistrate - I received a crown-piece from Tyrrell, which I marked, and when he was discharged I gave it to Mr. Field; Mr. Tyrrell was before the Magistrate, but not Mrs. Tyrrell.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1848">
                  JOHN 
                  FIELD
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1848" type="surname" value="FIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1848" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1848" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an inspector of counterfeit coin. I received this crown-piece from Oldis on the 29th of July, at Guildhall.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1849">
                  MORY 
                  SAVAGE
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1849" type="surname" value="SAVAGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1849" type="given" value="MORY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1849" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of Robert Savage, and keep an oyster-shop in Harp-alley. On Thursday, the 5th of August, about half-past twelve o'clock at night, the prisoner bought 1d. worth of oysters, which he paid 1d. for and went away; he came again in ten minutes with another man, had 4d. worth of oysters and 1d. of bread - the prisoner paid me a shilling; I did not examine it - I asked my brother-in-law to examine it; he thought it good, and put it on the counter, but did not mix it with any other - after he left the watchman came up; I then sounded it on the counter - the watchman said, "You have given that man changed altbough I cautioned you:" the prisoner had new been gone a minute - my brother-in-law went in search of him I saw him in custody on the Sunday.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1850">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HENRY HART
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1850" type="surname" value="HENRY HART"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1850" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1850" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was in Savage's shop - I did not notice the prisoner; I received a shilling from my sister-in-law - I thought it good, and gave it back to her; the watchman came up - I then looked at it, and pronounced it bad; I went with the watchman to look for the prisoner, but could not find him - I saw the shilling at Guildhall, and knew it by a mark which I put on it; I had given it to the officer on the previous night.</p>
               <p>Prisoner. I saw him put the shilling into his pocket. Witness. I did not.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1851">
                  MARK 
                  ADAMS
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1851" type="surname" value="ADAMS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1851" type="given" value="MARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1851" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a watchman. I was by Savage's shop on the 5th of August, between twelve and one o'clock at night, and saw the prisoner give her 1d. - as soon as he was gone I spoke to Savage; I afterwards endeavoured to apprehend him, and took him on Sunday morning, in Black Horse-court - I am certain of him.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310908-253-person1852">
                  JOHN 
                  BADDEN
               <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1852" type="surname" value="BADDEN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1852" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310908-253-person1852" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I was on duty in Harp-alley, and received a shilling from Hart, which I have now.</p>
               <p>MR. FIELD. This crown-piece and shilling are both counterfeits, and both cast in a mould - I was before the Magistrate on the first charge; it was understood to be the first he had uttered.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18310908-253-verdict1303" type="verdictDescription">
